":"1121","before 1120":"vóór 1120","1120":"1120","after 1121":"na 1121","1095":"1095","about 1120":"circa 1120","Clopton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Clopton, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wickhambrook, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Wickhambrook, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1095–after 1121":"about 1095–after 1121","1095–Female":"1095–Deceased","1120–1211":"1120–1211","1095–1121":"1095–1121","about 1095":"about 1095","1211":"1211","1121":"1121","before 1120":"before 1120","1120":"1120","after 1121":"after 1121","1095":"1095","about 1120":"about 1120","Clopton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Clopton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Wickhambrook, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Wickhambrook, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Peche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: unexplained.","German: possibly a variant of   Pech   ‘pitch, tar’.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Peče</b> or of its Germanized form   Petsche  , which is also a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Pech","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Jose, Manuel, Alvaro, Diego, Edelmira, Emilio, Francisco, Gilberto, Jorge, Jose Angel.  German Gerhard, Hans, Ilse, Lutz, Manfred, Wolf.","Czech and Slovak; Sorbian (<b>Pěch</b> and <b>P'ech</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Petr</i> (Czech), <i>Pětš</i> (Lower Sorbian), and   Peter   (Slovak). This is also a Germanized form of the Upper Sorbian cognate <b>Pjech</b>.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>pech</i> (German <i>Pech</i>) ‘pitch, tar’, presumably a nickname for someone with exceptionally dark skin or hair, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who prepared, sold, or used pitch. This may in part also be the origin of a homonymic Polish, Czech, and Slovak surname (compare above and below)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Peche was born about 1095, in Clopton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. He married Lady Lady Peche before 1120, in Clopton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1121, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1095–after 1121":"umbes 1095–pärast 1121","1095–Female":"1095–Surnud","1120–1211":"1120–1211","1095–1121":"1095–1121","about 1095":"umbes 1095","1211":"1211","1121":"1121","before 1120":"enne 1120","1120":"1120","after 1121":"pärast 1121","1095":"1095","about 1120":"umbes 1120","Clopton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Clopton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wickhambrook, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Wickhambroo